    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-05-21T20:09:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-05-21T20:09:00-05:00" n="355"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d355">
                <head>355. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to
                        <gloss type="to">the Embassy in Japan</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d355fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> 6 <gloss
                            target="#t_CHIC1">CHICOM</gloss>. Confidential. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BWG1">Winthrop G. Brown</persName>; cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BCW1">Charles W. Bray, Jr.</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BWT2">William T. Breer</persName>, and
                            <persName>Robert</persName> Emmons; and approved by
                            <persName>Brown</persName>. Repeated to Saigon for Assistant Secretary
                            <persName corresp="#p_GM2">Green</persName> and to Hong Kong.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-05-22T01:09:00+00:00">May 22, 1971, 0109Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>90063. Subject: Press Speculation on <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss>.</p>
                <p>The Department has been receiving spate of inquiries about reports that US has
                    decided a new <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> policy. Some of these
                    appear to have Japanese source.</p>
                <p>In addition Reuters today reports that US and Japanese policy planners at Lake
                    Kawaguchi meeting agreed China’s entry into <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                    unavoidable and that their countries should try to keep Formosa in the <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>, even if <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>
                    allowed to enter.</p>
                <p>Department does not wish to encourage or participate in speculation about future
                    US <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> policy, and is replying to all
                    inquiries that policy review this subject has not yet been completed and no
                    decisions have been made. Some press have been advised on background that in
                    course of review, US has consulted with other countries including Japan.</p>
                <p>With respect to Reuters report mentioned above, Department will simply state its
                    long-established position that we are opposed to admission of <gloss
                        target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> at cost of expulsion of <gloss target="#t_GRC1"
                        >GRC</gloss> and will decline to speculate on voting prospects for Assembly
                    this fall.</p>
                <pb facs="0723" n="686" xml:id="pg_686"/>
                <p>You may wish inform <gloss target="#t_GOJ1">GOJ</gloss> that leaks of this kind
                    make candid consultation very difficult.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rogers</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
